        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary">1. Strategic Detachment</h1>
        <p class="text-lg italic text-secondary/80">"Te mouille pas" - Don't get yourself wet</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        In a world that demands constant involvement, wisdom lies in knowing when to step back. Strategic detachment 
        isn't apathy—it's vigilance. It's the difference between thoughtful observation and impulsive participation. 
        This French expression literally means "don't get yourself wet," but metaphorically warns against diving 
        into turbulent waters where you have nothing to gain and everything to lose.
      </p>
      
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">The Psychology Behind Involvement</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Humans are social creatures with a built-in tendency to involve themselves in group dynamics. This served 
        our ancestors well in small tribes, but in modern complex organizations and social networks, this instinct 
        often backfires. Every conflict, every drama, every heated discussion feels urgent and important, triggering 
        our ancient need to pick sides and engage.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        The problem is that most modern conflicts are not about survival—they're about ego, territory, and status. 
        When you insert yourself into these dynamics without clear benefit or necessity, you expose yourself to 
        risk without proportional reward. Worse, you often become the target simply for being present.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-secondary/5 p-6 rounded-box border border-primary/20 backdrop-blur-sm mb-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-3">The Golden Rule of Strategic Detachment:</h4>
        <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm mb-3">Before engaging in any situation, ask yourself these three questions:</p>
        <ul class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">What's really at stake here?</strong> (Often it's less than it appears)</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">What's my actual role or responsibility?</strong> (Often it's none)</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">What are the potential consequences of my involvement?</strong> (Often they're significant)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Case Study: The Office Drama Trap</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Sarah works in marketing at a tech company. Two departments are feuding over budget allocation—sales wants 
        more money for leads, while product development needs resources for a critical update. Both sides approach 
        Sarah, seeking her "opinion" and "support." The conversations become increasingly heated, with accusations 
        of incompetence and hidden agendas flying.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Detached Approach:</strong> Sarah listens to both sides with genuine interest, asks clarifying 
        questions, but avoids taking positions. "That's a really complex situation. I can see why you're frustrated. 
        What do you think would be the ideal outcome?" She gathers intelligence about office dynamics without 
        creating enemies or commitments.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Result:</strong> When the dust settles (the CEO makes the final decision), both sides still 
        view Sarah as neutral and trustworthy. She's avoided becoming a casualty of a war that wasn't hers to fight, 
        while gaining valuable insight into organizational dynamics and power structures.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">When Detachment Becomes Essential</h3>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-primary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">Family Drama</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Extended family conflicts, divorce proceedings of friends, sibling rivalries. Unless you're directly involved or can genuinely help, stay out.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-secondary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-2">Workplace Politics</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Interdepartmental feuds, management changes, rumor mills. Observe, learn, but don't pick sides unless your job depends on it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-secondary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-2">Social Media Controversies</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Online debates, cancel culture situations, viral outrage. Your opinion rarely matters and almost always costs you something.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-primary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">Friend Group Conflicts</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Romantic drama between friends, friendship breakups, social hierarchies. Maintain relationships with individuals, not sides.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Advanced Techniques</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Switzerland Strategy:</strong> Like the neutral country that profits from staying out of wars, 
        you can benefit from conflicts by being the stable, trustworthy party that both sides can confide in. 
        This requires discipline—never repeat what you hear, never take sides, never give advice that could be 
        seen as picking a winner.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Information Asymmetry:</strong> Detachment gives you access to information from multiple sources 
        without the bias that comes from being partisan. You see the full picture while others see only their 
        side's perspective. This knowledge becomes a significant advantage in decision-making.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Long Game:</strong> While others burn bridges and create enemies through impulsive involvement, 
        your detached approach preserves relationships and options. Years later, when former enemies need to work 
        together, you're often the bridge that makes it possible.
      </p>

